Body: Description: Returning to previous issue from ticket 412503. NEA showing historical data in scans. Scans are set to only 5 levels and need to go to at least 8 levels. John Deere will need assistance making these changes and setting up the scans, plus follow up review.
Invitation updated. Attendees: No attendees listed
Invitation updated. Attendees: Dusty Grayson, Scott Prigge
Next Steps Updated: Meeting set for Next week.

What We've Learned Updated: > What is the impact of the issue on your business? 

We can't rely on the data for current use cases.

> Who is affected by this issue? 
Auditors, and anyone else who may have valid use cases for the data.


> When did this issue start?  
Unknown. Most likely, for a long time (multiple years). The product has always been lacking administrative attention in our company.

What We've Learned Updated: Current FileSystem details in question is limited to 3 lvl deep so the scans are not updating the objects below this lvl.

Dusty Grayson: Applet Log level not respecting the console settings

posted in SWAT Teams: Product Discussions, PM Q&A, Feedback / NEA DAG on Friday, February 7, 2025 5:12 PM

 

 Robert Minichino Friday 5:17 PM

the applet server logs default to DEBUG, but even at DEBUG level they shouldn't be very large

the log level for the FSAA_Applet_Server log is controlled by the NLog.config file in the FSAA folder for proxy servers installed as a service, and for automatic deployment by the NLog.config file in StealthAUDITPrivateAssembliesFILESYSTEMACCESSApplet

the applet server logs default to DEBUG, but even at DEBUG level they shouldn't be very large

Dusty Grayson

Yesterday 10:08 AM

Within that file we would edit the following as needed: Error, Warning, etc... assuming case sensitivity.

 

           <rules>

<logger name="*FSAA*" minlevel="Debug" writeTo="ServerFile" />

<logger name="*Kestrel*" minlevel="Info" writeTo="ServerFile" />

<logger name="*HttpsConnectionMiddleware*" minlevel="Debug" writeTo="ServerFile" />

<logger name="*" minlevel="Warn" writeTo="ServerFile" />

</rules>

Robert Minichino

Yesterday 10:15 AM

Warn not warning, I don't believe it's case-sensitive but it can't hurt to keep it consistent

 

you would change the FSAA line

the others should be fine as-is currently, there is no retention setting or automatic cleanup for these log files, we're planning on fixing that in the future
